data.content:
Yes — two improvements depending on your MSTest version:

**Simplest: use `[DataRow]` for inline constants**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**If you need computed data: strongly-typed tuples (MSTest 3.x+)**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| `[DataRow]` | Simplest, no extra property | Values must be compile-time constants |
| Typed `DynamicData` | Type-safe, supports computed values | Requires MSTest 3.4+ |
| `object[]` (yours) | Works everywhere | No type safety, boxing |

Use `[DataRow]` for simple cases like yours. Switch to typed `DynamicData` when you need runtime-computed test data.
